55
00:03:11.100 --> 00:03:15.060
I'll talk about a question that hopefully some of you will find interesting and

56
00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:16.840
maybe a little bit provocative, namely,

57
00:03:17.980 --> 00:03:21.620
what do we really know about the mutations that we have found to

58
00:03:21.660 --> 00:03:25.600
be enriched in cancer genomes? Are those necessarily mutations

59
00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:29.620
that cause cancer, or are maybe some of them just an inheritance from the normal

60
00:03:29.640 --> 00:03:33.260
tissue evolution that precedes carcinogenesis as we age?

61
00:03:34.740 --> 00:03:38.160
So which mutations cause cancer? Seems like a very simple

62
00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:42.080
question. And of course, through big cancer genome sequencing efforts

63
00:03:42.140 --> 00:03:46.130
like the TCGA, PEACOCK, and many others that you're familiar

64
00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:49.740
with, you'll know that we have very good, robust methods for

65
00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:53.200
identifying cancer drivers. Many variations of them

66
00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:57.760
are available, but typically, the approach is something like we

67
00:03:57.780 --> 00:04:00.160
sequence a whole bunch of cancers from the same tissue.

68
00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:03.540
We look at the variants found in an individual gene.

69
00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:07.859
Some of them are synonymous mutations that don't cause any protein changes.

70
00:04:07.900 --> 00:04:11.320
Some of them are non-synonymous mutations that do change the protein.

71
00:04:11.670 --> 00:04:15.660
And we look at their relative ratios and really conclude that

72
00:04:15.740 --> 00:04:19.510
if a gene is enriched for mutations that change its function, then

73
00:04:19.921 --> 00:04:22.780
this gene is likely to be a cancer-causing gene.

74
00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:27.940
So mutations in gene X, they occur frequently or show signs

75
00:04:27.960 --> 00:04:30.980
of positive selection. We conclude that they cause cancer.

76
00:04:32.340 --> 00:04:35.700
However, one of the big conceptual, I will say,

77
00:04:35.860 --> 00:04:39.840
remodelings that has taken place in the last 10 to 15 years

78
00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:43.100
is that we've come to understand that the tissues in our

79
00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:47.940
bodies contain lots and lots of cells that contain ample mutations

80
00:04:47.980 --> 00:04:51.520
that were previously thought to be more specific to the cancer than they really

81
00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:55.040
are. So mutations arise during somatic evolution all the

82
00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:58.490
time. They arise during embryonic development.

83
00:04:58.710 --> 00:05:02.460
They arise as our cells turn over for the homeostasis of our

84
00:05:02.500 --> 00:05:06.350
tissues. And then some of the mutations that occur in our cells, if

85
00:05:06.380 --> 00:05:10.190
they confer a competitive advantage to the cell, can expand

86
00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:14.030
and form this now famous patchwork of mutant clones that

87
00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:18.220
inhabits most of the self-renewing tissues that

88
00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:22.120
we have in our body. And of course, a big topic of the session today,

89
00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:25.880
we think that the structure of these clones, the frequency of the mutations

90
00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:30.120
that are sitting in these clones really affect our risk of

91
00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:34.280
getting cancer down the line. And of course, when the cancer then

92
00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:35.550
emerges from one of these

93
00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:40.200
background mutant clones that are sitting

94
00:05:40.260 --> 00:05:40.720
everywhere,

95
00:05:41.960 --> 00:05:45.280
it's not only characterized by the mutations that really make it into a cancer, but

96
00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:48.340
it inherits all the mutations that were sometimes maybe

97
00:05:48.820 --> 00:05:49.780
innocently

98
00:05:50.740 --> 00:05:53.660
acquired during this normal tissue evolution process.

99
00:05:54.540 --> 00:05:58.520
So what we now have to ask is, do signals of positive selections in cancer

100
00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:02.600
genomes reflect cancer causation necessarily, or are

101
00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:06.100
some of them may be merely an inheritance from normal tissue

102
00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:08.384
evolution?So you can think of it as

103
00:06:09.364 --> 00:06:12.664
a Venn diagram like this. There is going to be mutations that are positively

104
00:06:12.724 --> 00:06:15.924
selected in our normal tissues, and there's going to be mutations that cause

105
00:06:15.984 --> 00:06:18.904
cancer. Without a doubt, there will be a significant overlap.

106
00:06:19.264 --> 00:06:22.544
But how large the overlap is and in which of these categories

107
00:06:23.164 --> 00:06:27.124
any one individual mutation belongs is an open question and I think an exciting

108
00:06:27.204 --> 00:06:27.564
question.

109
00:06:29.224 --> 00:06:32.804
So, a postdoc in my lab who is a formal

110
00:06:32.844 --> 00:06:35.584
mathematician and a probabilist started thinking about

111
00:06:36.784 --> 00:06:40.764
a rigorous way of trying to incorporate the data that we currently have to answer

112
00:06:40.784 --> 00:06:44.764
the question of, if we find a mutation in the cancer genome, can we figure out

113
00:06:44.804 --> 00:06:45.204
whether it's

114
00:06:46.124 --> 00:06:49.524
really a mutation that is selected during normal tissue evolution, or is it

115
00:06:49.584 --> 00:06:50.224
cancer-causing?

116
00:06:51.264 --> 00:06:54.374
And so the first thing that we have to do is to come up with a definition of

117
00:06:54.384 --> 00:06:55.644
carcinogenicity.

118
00:06:56.804 --> 00:07:00.504
A true probabilist thinks of this definition as

119
00:07:00.944 --> 00:07:04.224
a ratio of rates. So it's actually really simple.

120
00:07:04.364 --> 00:07:08.173
Think of a cell that has a particular mutation Z, your favorite mutation, you can

121
00:07:08.184 --> 00:07:08.853
think of it right now,

122
00:07:09.684 --> 00:07:13.204
and this cell causes a transformation

123
00:07:13.524 --> 00:07:16.184
into a lineage that will eventually be diagnosed as a cancer.

124
00:07:18.484 --> 00:07:22.304
At the same time, there is a cell without this mutation Z, and this cell can of

125
00:07:22.344 --> 00:07:24.844
course also cause cancer for whatever reason,

126
00:07:26.084 --> 00:07:28.064
but it's going to do this at a different rate, R0.

127
00:07:28.644 --> 00:07:32.604
And so we think of the mutation Z's carcinogenic effect as really just the ratio

128
00:07:32.624 --> 00:07:36.564
between the rate R1 and R0. So how much more likely is a

129
00:07:36.584 --> 00:07:40.144
cell that carries the mutation to found a truly malignant lineage

130
00:07:40.184 --> 00:07:42.374
over a cell that doesn't have the mutation?

131
00:07:44.244 --> 00:07:47.804
The nice thing about this carcinogenic effect is that it's really easy to

132
00:07:47.864 --> 00:07:51.124
estimate from data. We really need only two things for it.

133
00:07:51.824 --> 00:07:55.784
So we need Y, the frequency of the mutation among cancers

134
00:07:55.824 --> 00:07:58.944
of that type, and sorry, I just see people taking pictures.

135
00:07:59.004 --> 00:08:02.464
This is all on bioRxiv. Of course, you're still welcome to take as many pictures as

136
00:08:02.504 --> 00:08:06.444
you like, but all of this is on bioRxiv, and the paper is actually in press as

137
00:08:06.504 --> 00:08:09.724
well. It's about to come out in "Nature Genetics" within the next few weeks.

138
00:08:09.784 --> 00:08:09.844
So,

139
00:08:12.304 --> 00:08:13.404
just to make life easier for you .

140
00:08:15.024 --> 00:08:18.784
So yes, we only need two things. So we need Y, the frequency of the

141
00:08:18.824 --> 00:08:21.604
mutation among cancers of that type. So let's walk through an example.

142
00:08:22.024 --> 00:08:25.184
Let's say we care about esophageal squamous cell carcinoma.

143
00:08:25.204 --> 00:08:28.804
We can go into TCGA or Peacock, and then for mutations

144
00:08:29.184 --> 00:08:33.144
that are frequently found to be mutated in esophageal squamous cell carcinoma, we

145
00:08:33.184 --> 00:08:36.814
can look at the frequency. So how many cancers of that type carry that

146
00:08:36.865 --> 00:08:39.564
mutation? Which, for example, for P53 is around 80.

147
00:08:40.605 --> 00:08:44.464
Now we need X, the frequency of the mutation among normal

148
00:08:44.504 --> 00:08:48.264
cells in the same tissue of origin, ideally in the same

149
00:08:48.964 --> 00:08:51.124
patients. So we'll talk about this more in just a moment.

150
00:08:52.424 --> 00:08:54.764
But this data has for a long time not been available.

151
00:08:54.884 --> 00:08:58.794
It is now more and more being generated for various tissues, which is a wonderful

152
00:08:58.824 --> 00:09:02.004
thing. So for the esophagus, there's an excellent set of papers.

153
00:09:02.084 --> 00:09:05.724
Actually, I'm just quoting one here, where investigators have gone in

154
00:09:05.864 --> 00:09:09.704
here from Seishi Ogawa's group in Japan, and they have deep

155
00:09:09.804 --> 00:09:13.064
sequenced a very small biopsy of the normal esophageal

156
00:09:13.124 --> 00:09:14.164
mucosa

157
00:09:15.404 --> 00:09:19.064
from people who also had surgery for esophageal cancer and

158
00:09:20.104 --> 00:09:23.904
basically genotyped these cells to look at what the frequency of these

159
00:09:23.944 --> 00:09:27.404
mutations in the normal tissue is that didn't give rise to the cancer and also has

160
00:09:27.464 --> 00:09:30.184
no clonal relationship to the cancer that arose.

161
00:09:31.364 --> 00:09:35.324
And so once we have these two frequencies, we can project mutations into this

162
00:09:35.384 --> 00:09:35.964
space,

163
00:09:36.924 --> 00:09:40.804
which is interesting to look at because it classifies mutations

164
00:09:40.844 --> 00:09:44.584
as strongly carcinogenic, meaning that they're much more likely to be found in a

165
00:09:44.644 --> 00:09:47.964
cancer of a particular type, but much less likely in the corresponding normal

166
00:09:48.004 --> 00:09:51.464
tissue, or cancer inhibiting, which means that even

167
00:09:51.484 --> 00:09:55.284
though all the genes that we're considering here are bona fide esophageal

168
00:09:55.324 --> 00:09:59.244
squamous cell carcinoma drivers as defined by TCGA, they may, in

169
00:09:59.284 --> 00:10:03.004
some cases, actually be mutated more frequently in the normal tissue

170
00:10:03.064 --> 00:10:06.984
than in the corresponding cancer, which would make them cancer inhibiting, kind

171
00:10:07.024 --> 00:10:10.784
of really turning the world upside down for a cancer

172
00:10:10.844 --> 00:10:14.764
geneticist. And then the carcinogenic effect estimate is really just the odds ratio

173
00:10:14.804 --> 00:10:16.784
of these frequencies. So let's do it.

174
00:10:17.944 --> 00:10:19.724
Let's actually put the genes in this space.

175
00:10:20.684 --> 00:10:24.124
You will see some that are entirely

176
00:10:24.144 --> 00:10:26.043
unsurprising. So for example, P53

177
00:10:26.884 --> 00:10:30.684
is coming out with carcinogenic effect standing in the thousands, meaning that

178
00:10:30.944 --> 00:10:34.164
it's much, much more frequent in esophageal squamous cell carcinoma than in the

179
00:10:34.224 --> 00:10:34.904
corresponding

180
00:10:35.924 --> 00:10:37.404
normal cells in the esophagus.

181
00:10:38.344 --> 00:10:42.304
However, on the other side, we also have other examples that now at this

182
00:10:42.344 --> 00:10:46.204
point, a famous notch one, which we've for a long time considered to be a

183
00:10:46.224 --> 00:10:49.704
strong driver of esophageal squamous cell carcinoma because it's so frequently

184
00:10:49.764 --> 00:10:53.424
mutated in that cancer. But this type of sequencing has now shown

185
00:10:53.484 --> 00:10:57.004
us that while it's actually even more frequent in the normal esophagus,

186
00:10:57.424 --> 00:11:01.344
and we have to kind of reclassify it now as tumor formation inhibiting.

187
00:11:01.694 --> 00:11:05.644
And there are some really great experiments from Phil Jones' lab that

188
00:11:05.684 --> 00:11:09.404
have experimentally corroborated the tumor inhibiting function

189
00:11:09.484 --> 00:11:13.364
of notch mutations. And then maybe to me, most

190
00:11:13.404 --> 00:11:15.904
interesting is this line one here.

191
00:11:16.344 --> 00:11:20.184
That's carcinogenic effect one. That means those mutations or mutations in

192
00:11:20.204 --> 00:11:23.964
those genes, according to this analysis, have very little effect on the

193
00:11:23.984 --> 00:11:26.184
probability of a cell becoming malignant.

194
00:11:26.224 --> 00:11:29.664
And there are some pretty famous cancer drivers here, including PIK3CA,

195
00:11:30.184 --> 00:11:32.164
FAD1, EP300.

196
00:11:33.084 --> 00:11:35.684
I'm going to talk about some of them, in particular PIK3CA,

197
00:11:36.904 --> 00:11:37.664
in more depth.

198
00:11:38.544 --> 00:11:41.544
But really what it means is that these mutations are no more frequent in the cancer

199
00:11:41.644 --> 00:11:44.504
than they would be in the corresponding normal tissue,

200
00:11:45.544 --> 00:11:45.804
really

201
00:11:47.204 --> 00:11:50.764
at least at the most

202
00:11:51.444 --> 00:11:55.204
naive interpretation, inconsistent with a strong carcinogenic effect of

203
00:11:55.484 --> 00:11:55.984
PIK3CA.

204
00:11:57.544 --> 00:11:59.044
So we can do this for other organs now.

205
00:11:59.404 --> 00:12:00.824
Here is just an example from the blood

206
00:12:01.704 --> 00:12:05.144
where you can again see that some mutations have extremely large

207
00:12:05.164 --> 00:12:09.124
carcinogenic effects. They very frequently occur in AML, but almost never

208
00:12:09.144 --> 00:12:13.104
in the normal blood. But then some of the most frequent mutations that are found

209
00:12:13.144 --> 00:12:16.704
in AML, including TET2 and DNMT3A, SXL1,

210
00:12:17.164 --> 00:12:20.804
you see that they have relatively low carcinogenic effects and actually don't

211
00:12:20.824 --> 00:12:24.144
really do much to lineage in terms of pushing it in the direction of

212
00:12:24.204 --> 00:12:27.784
AML.Very briefly, just in case you're wondering, we compared our

213
00:12:27.804 --> 00:12:31.344
carcinogenic effects to independent estimates of AML

214
00:12:31.484 --> 00:12:35.304
risk of people who had blood sample taken, and then later

215
00:12:35.364 --> 00:12:38.514
years down the line, they developed AML, and there's a great paper

216
00:12:39.804 --> 00:12:43.784
by Gu et al. that calculated hazard ratios for a number

217
00:12:43.824 --> 00:12:47.624
of genes based on these data, and they

218
00:12:47.664 --> 00:12:51.644
agree really well with what we get with carcinogenic effects estimates,

219
00:12:51.684 --> 00:12:55.644
except that we didn't have to go through the trouble of looking

220
00:12:55.744 --> 00:12:59.544
for these rare samples where you have pre-AML blood and then the

221
00:12:59.584 --> 00:13:01.684
corresponding cancer. So that's kind of neat.

222
00:13:02.464 --> 00:13:06.074
However, and so this very much speaks to the topic of this

223
00:13:06.124 --> 00:13:09.864
session here, namely genetic and environmental

224
00:13:10.744 --> 00:13:12.484
risks for cancer development.

225
00:13:13.624 --> 00:13:15.624
There's one thing that is

226
00:13:16.464 --> 00:13:20.384
making this analysis a little bit difficult, and that is that in order to

227
00:13:20.404 --> 00:13:24.044
do it properly, you really need normal tissue data

228
00:13:24.164 --> 00:13:28.144
from the same people that you analyze the cancers of. Why is that?

229
00:13:28.844 --> 00:13:32.634
Well, it's because selective pressures on our tissues, and

230
00:13:32.664 --> 00:13:36.634
therefore the clonal evolution of our tissues, can really vary very much from

231
00:13:36.644 --> 00:13:40.294
person to person, and presumably the cancer risk that goes with

232
00:13:40.344 --> 00:13:41.364
that variant

233
00:13:42.704 --> 00:13:45.964
is quite different as well. So germline variants,

234
00:13:46.364 --> 00:13:50.184
lifestyle factors like what you eat, what you drink, medical history,

235
00:13:50.264 --> 00:13:54.164
whether you've had chemotherapy or not, all of these factors profoundly

236
00:13:54.244 --> 00:13:56.784
affect how your normal tissues will evolve.

237
00:13:56.824 --> 00:14:00.504
They will change the frequency of cancer driving

238
00:14:00.524 --> 00:14:04.384
mutations in your tissues. And so in order to get a fair comparison, we really

239
00:14:04.464 --> 00:14:07.684
need normal tissue sequencing data from the same people

240
00:14:08.804 --> 00:14:10.624
that we get the cancers from. So that

241
00:14:11.864 --> 00:14:14.884
would be the ideal world. Really, really hard to obtain.

242
00:14:15.244 --> 00:14:19.164
So what David wanted to know was, can we actually identify carcinogenic

