00:28:27.868 --> 00:28:30.868
They both give activating initiating mutations.

494
00:28:30.908 --> 00:28:34.708
So we can use this, and in fact extend this to a mutational

495
00:28:34.788 --> 00:28:38.728
signature for DMBA to find exactly the trinucleotide

496
00:28:38.808 --> 00:28:41.968
signature, which Mike Stratton talked about the other day.

497
00:28:43.048 --> 00:28:45.268
And we can look for that signature in tumors

498
00:28:45.348 --> 00:28:48.728
initiated by this single dose of DMBA.

499
00:28:49.148 --> 00:28:52.467
So when you do that, you see the purple columns here

500
00:28:53.248 --> 00:28:57.028
represent the number of mutations in a tumor. Each column is a tumor.

501
00:28:58.468 --> 00:29:01.968
The SBS DMBA is the trinucleotide signature

502
00:29:02.588 --> 00:29:04.648
for that single dose of the carcinogen.

503
00:29:05.228 --> 00:29:08.948
So some of the tumors have up to 30,000 mutations in their tumor

504
00:29:09.008 --> 00:29:12.088
genomes. Some have relatively few.

505
00:29:12.648 --> 00:29:15.208
Important thing for this slide is this part here.

506
00:29:15.268 --> 00:29:19.238
These are the tumors that came from the delay experiment where you treat and then

507
00:29:19.288 --> 00:29:23.118
you wait for up to a year. Right? So this tumor here has

508
00:29:23.168 --> 00:29:24.838
about 50,000 mutations

509
00:29:26.008 --> 00:29:29.688
that were induced on day one by that single dose of the carcinogen.

510
00:29:29.758 --> 00:29:32.198
And that includes Ras, it includes p53.

511
00:29:32.608 --> 00:29:36.268
But nevertheless, that cell, that single cell, sat there for a year and

512
00:29:36.328 --> 00:29:37.668
didn't actually do anything.

513
00:29:38.888 --> 00:29:41.928
They all required the promoter. So Bern Bloom and Shubik were absolutely right.

514
00:29:42.068 --> 00:29:43.888
The promotion is the rate-limiting step.

515
00:29:44.348 --> 00:29:48.168
These are genetic models of cancer here induced by KRAS

516
00:29:48.208 --> 00:29:51.768
G12D in the skin, and then followed by either

517
00:29:51.848 --> 00:29:54.988
wounding or TPA. So no mutagenic exposures.

518
00:29:55.558 --> 00:29:59.368
And these have vanishingly few mutations, and the only recurrent mutation is this

519
00:29:59.428 --> 00:30:03.348
one here. You don't see any other recurrent somatic mutations in

520
00:30:03.428 --> 00:30:05.308
these tumors.

521
00:30:06.208 --> 00:30:09.588
So all you need is that one mutation plus the wounding or the TPA.

522
00:30:11.568 --> 00:30:15.408
So what I've told you then is that these RAS mutant cells can

523
00:30:16.008 --> 00:30:19.788
persist a long time in the normal skin and not

524
00:30:19.908 --> 00:30:23.348
actually do anything. And those of you who've been following the clonal

525
00:30:23.428 --> 00:30:26.748
competition literature over the years will be aware of some of these papers.

526
00:30:27.968 --> 00:30:30.328
These are from the group of Valentina Greco.

527
00:30:30.568 --> 00:30:31.068
There's also

528
00:30:31.968 --> 00:30:34.428
other groups. Phil Jones and others have

529
00:30:34.628 --> 00:30:37.968
shownThat mutant cells are

530
00:30:38.028 --> 00:30:41.848
removed from normal tissue by tissue damage or by

531
00:30:41.948 --> 00:30:45.888
aging. In their case, the mutant cells get shoved out, and

532
00:30:45.928 --> 00:30:48.428
this is a phenomenon of clonal competition that was

533
00:30:49.828 --> 00:30:53.508
started many years ago in Drosophila, extended to other

534
00:30:53.568 --> 00:30:57.448
developmental model systems. But we have these two apparently opposing

535
00:30:57.468 --> 00:31:01.248
kind of views. One, your RAS mutations are permanent, the other, they

536
00:31:01.308 --> 00:31:03.448
get kicked out by their neighbors.

537
00:31:04.648 --> 00:31:06.968
So we've been using a number of approaches to try and

538
00:31:07.948 --> 00:31:10.688
reconcile these two different types of observations

539
00:31:11.608 --> 00:31:13.628
using these types of assays here,

540
00:31:15.308 --> 00:31:18.848
where we take a normal young epithelium, no obvious

541
00:31:18.908 --> 00:31:22.728
mutations. You have some cells with sporadic mutations.

542
00:31:23.228 --> 00:31:24.748
If you treat with a--

543
00:31:25.948 --> 00:31:29.928
That could be induced by DMBA. It could also be spontaneous, as we'll come

544
00:31:29.968 --> 00:31:33.448
back to later. Then some of these clones begin to expand,

545
00:31:34.348 --> 00:31:38.188
in our case, under the influence of exposure to a promoter like

546
00:31:38.248 --> 00:31:42.008
TPA. So you get these larger purple clones, and they're the

547
00:31:42.068 --> 00:31:45.928
ones that go on and give tumors. But there are all these other mutations in

548
00:31:45.988 --> 00:31:49.878
here. And to find them, we use this technique,

549
00:31:49.968 --> 00:31:52.548
which was developed by TwinStrand.

550
00:31:53.548 --> 00:31:57.528
Jesse Salk was instrumental in getting this

551
00:31:57.568 --> 00:31:59.208
technique going, starting the company.

552
00:32:01.088 --> 00:32:04.128
And Jesse has collaborated on many of these studies.

553
00:32:04.188 --> 00:32:07.948
So the interesting point, I think, which is also relevant to the previous

554
00:32:08.068 --> 00:32:08.428
talk,

555
00:32:09.388 --> 00:32:11.648
these are DMBA-induced mutations.

556
00:32:12.048 --> 00:32:15.908
But we can also have spontaneous mutations in exactly the same tissue,

557
00:32:16.388 --> 00:32:19.888
where all of us sitting here are acquiring spontaneous

