01:11:55.280 --> 01:11:55.600
smoker.

1242
01:11:57.680 --> 01:12:01.340
And to answer the question of how many cells may

1243
01:12:01.400 --> 01:12:05.340
harbor driver mutations in our tissues, or what is the

1244
01:12:05.380 --> 01:12:09.120
probability of every mutation to occur, we may be tempted to do

1245
01:12:09.160 --> 01:12:12.760
the very simple back of the envelope calculation and say, "Okay, we have

1246
01:12:12.960 --> 01:12:16.880
3,000 mutations along the genome, and we have this number of bases in

1247
01:12:16.920 --> 01:12:19.940
the genome, so this is the probability." And this would be completely wrong,

1248
01:12:20.420 --> 01:12:22.860
because the mutations are not distributed

1249
01:12:23.920 --> 01:12:27.720
equally along the genome, right? They have very high preferences for

1250
01:12:27.760 --> 01:12:31.620
some regions that are more likely to mutate and some genes than others, depending

1251
01:12:31.640 --> 01:12:35.380
on expression, chromatin openness, histone marks, and many other

1252
01:12:35.460 --> 01:12:39.100
things. And also at trinucleotide level, you know about

1253
01:12:39.140 --> 01:12:41.960
mutational signatures and basically different

1254
01:12:42.460 --> 01:12:46.280
mutagens have very strong preferences for certain

1255
01:12:46.300 --> 01:12:50.180
sites. So we need to take this into account to be able

1256
01:12:50.300 --> 01:12:53.720
to do the estimation of the mutation probability per

1257
01:12:53.780 --> 01:12:56.920
site.And this is what Axel has done.

1258
01:12:57.380 --> 01:13:00.939
He has developed MutRisk that estimates the probability of each mutation to occur

1259
01:13:00.980 --> 01:13:04.900
in normal tissues, and this accounts for the overall mutation rate in that

1260
01:13:04.960 --> 01:13:06.580
cells, in that tissue, in that donor,

1261
01:13:07.500 --> 01:13:10.380
mutation rate variability per gene and per mutation type.

1262
01:13:11.620 --> 01:13:15.580
And then once we have this MutRisk model, we can put a probability

1263
01:13:15.620 --> 01:13:19.320
of any site in the genome to mutate in that person, in that

1264
01:13:19.380 --> 01:13:19.719
tissue.

1265
01:13:20.580 --> 01:13:23.940
And this is applying this to TP53

1266
01:13:24.920 --> 01:13:28.440
amino acid positions. And you can

1267
01:13:28.760 --> 01:13:32.580
very quickly see in a colon of a donor, you can very quickly see that there is a

1268
01:13:32.680 --> 01:13:36.340
huge inequality, so that there are some sites that have a very high

1269
01:13:36.380 --> 01:13:40.120
probability to mutate and some sites that have very low probability to mutate.

1270
01:13:40.580 --> 01:13:44.540
Right? So if you throw random mutations due to these mutational processes in a

1271
01:13:44.560 --> 01:13:48.460
